recordings.loc: William B. Bankhead National Forest (near  Moulton), Sipsey Wilderness Area, FS Rd. 208, Lawrence County, Alabama
recordings.rmk:
Unusual song-type for species (as far as I know), first part is typical BTNW, second part is somewhat reminiscent of a Cerulean Warbler.  In the recording, there are at least three counter-singing individuals, maybe four but did not keep notes at the time.  This is the only location in the Bankhead National Forest Sipsey Wilderness Area I've heard this song type.  First noticed it at this location in May of 2013.  Interestingly a Cerulean Warbler was found singing and photographed at this location 2013-05-09.  However I wonder if subsequent reports to eBird of Cerulean Warbler at this location may have been these atypical BTNWs.  Both times I've visited this site in 2013 and 2014 I've never had CERW  but have had visual of BTNWs singing this song type.

Recorded using iPhone 5s internal microphone and the Rode Rec. app.

recordings.loc: El Tizatillo, near Tegucigalpa
recordings.rmk: A group of at least 4 Black-throated Green Warblers, foraging in young encino oak (Quercus sapotifolia) at 4-7 m altitude. They were in the company of two Blue-headed Vireos, a Black-and-White Warbler and a Magnolia Warbler. A common winter visitor at the location, it rarely sings there except now, in migration. Songs weak (unaccented ending?), and the background noise from cicadas rather formidable, but three songs are audible on this cut. Two BT Green Warblers in this group were adult males, and two were either adult females or immature males. Not 100% sure which of these birds was singing during the recording.
